  "source": {
    "type": "article",
    "title": "大语言模型入门：从 token 到上下文",
    "author": "Google Machine Learning Crash Course",
    "account": "Google 机器学习速成课",
    "accountOrDomain": "Google 机器学习速成课",
    "url": "https://developers.google.com/machine-learning/crash-course/llm",
    "blocks": [
      {
        "id": "p-010",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "语言模型会估计一个 token 或一串 token 在上下文中出现的概率，因此可以支持文本生成、翻译、摘要等任务。大语言模型把这种预测能力扩展到更大的数据规模和更复杂的上下文关系中。"
      },
      {
        "id": "p-011",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "上下文是目标 token 周围的信息。模型使用上下文来提高预测准确性；相比只看固定短片段的传统 N-gram，循环神经网络和后来的 Transformer 能利用更长、更复杂的上下文。"
      },
      {
        "id": "p-012",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "N-gram 是按顺序排列的一组词。更长的 N-gram 可以提供更多上下文，但也更容易遇到数据稀疏问题：某些词序组合在训练数据里很少出现，模型就难以可靠估计它们的概率。"
      },
      {
        "id": "p-014",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "注意力机制让模型在生成当前 token 时，能够根据需要关注输入中的不同位置。它不是平均读取所有信息，而是学习哪些上下文片段更相关。"
      },
      {
        "id": "p-033",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "What is a language model?"
      },
      {
        "id": "p-034",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "A language model"
      },
      {
        "id": "p-035",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "estimates the probability of a token"
      },
      {
        "id": "p-036",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "or sequence of tokens occurring within a longer sequence of tokens. A token"
      },
      {
        "id": "p-037",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "could be a word, a subword (a subset of a word), or even a single character."
      },
      {
        "id": "p-062",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "Tokens are the atomic unit or smallest unit of language modeling."
      },
      {
        "id": "p-091",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "N-gram language models"
      },
      {
        "id": "p-092",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "N-grams are ordered sequences of words"
      },
      {
        "id": "p-093",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "used to build language models, where N is the number of words in the sequence."
      },
      {
        "id": "p-107",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "Given two words as input, a language model based on 3-grams can predict the"
      },
      {
        "id": "p-108",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "likelihood of the third word. For example, given the following two words:"
      },
      {
        "id": "p-119",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "Context"
      },
      {
        "id": "p-120",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "Humans can retain relatively long contexts. While watching Act 3 of a play, you"
      },
      {
        "id": "p-121",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "retain knowledge of characters introduced in Act 1. Similarly, the"
      },
      {
        "id": "p-122",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "punchline of a long joke makes you laugh because you can remember the context"
      },
      {
        "id": "p-123",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "from the joke's setup."
      },
      {
        "id": "p-124",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "In language models, context is helpful information before or after the"
      },
      {
        "id": "p-125",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "target token. Context can help a language model determine whether \"orange\""
      },
      {
        "id": "p-126",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "refers to a citrus fruit or a color."
      },
      {
        "id": "p-127",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "Context can help a language model make better predictions, but does a"
      },
      {
        "id": "p-128",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "3-gram provide sufficient context? Unfortunately, the only context a 3-gram"
      },
      {
        "id": "p-129",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "provides is the first two words. For example, the two words orange is doesn't"
      },
      {
        "id": "p-130",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "provide enough context for the language model to predict the third word."
      },
      {
        "id": "p-131",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "Due to lack of context, language models based on 3-grams make a lot of mistakes."
      },
      {
        "id": "p-132",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "Longer N-grams would certainly provide more context than shorter N-grams."
      },
      {
        "id": "p-133",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "However, as N grows, the relative occurrence of each instance decreases."
      },
      {
        "id": "p-134",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "When N becomes very large, the language model typically has only a single"
      },
      {
        "id": "p-135",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "instance of each occurrence of N tokens, which isn't very helpful in"
      },
      {
        "id": "p-136",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "predicting the target token."
      },
      {
        "id": "p-137",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "Recurrent neural networks"
      },
      {
        "id": "p-138",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "Recurrent neural"
      },
      {
        "id": "p-139",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "networks"
      },
      {
        "id": "p-140",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "provide more context than N-grams. A recurrent neural network is a type of"
      },
      {
        "id": "p-141",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "neural network that trains on"
      },
      {
        "id": "p-142",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "a sequence of tokens. For example, a recurrent neural network"
      },
      {
        "id": "p-143",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "can gradually learn (and learn to ignore) selected context from each word"
      },
      {
        "id": "p-144",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "in a sentence, kind of like you would when listening to someone speak."
      },
      {
        "id": "p-145",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "A large recurrent neural network can gain context from a passage of several"
      },
      {
        "id": "p-146",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "sentences."
      },
      {
        "id": "p-147",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "Although recurrent neural networks learn more context than N-grams, the amount"
      },
      {
        "id": "p-148",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "of useful context recurrent neural networks can intuit is still relatively"
      },
      {
        "id": "p-149",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "limited. Recurrent neural networks evaluate information \"token by token.\""
      },
      {
        "id": "p-150",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "In contrast, large language models&mdash;the topic of the next"
      },
      {
        "id": "p-151",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "section&mdash;can evaluate the whole context at once."
      },
      {
        "id": "p-152",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "Note that training recurrent neural networks for long contexts is constrained by"
      },
      {
        "id": "p-153",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "the vanishing gradient"
      },
      {
        "id": "p-154",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "problem ."
      }
    ],
    "rawInput": "https://developers.google.com/machine-learning/crash-course/llm"
  },
  "summaryCard": {
    "text": "语言模型通过估计token序列概率来实现文本生成、翻译等任务，本模块介绍其核心概念、N-gram模型、上下文机制及循环神经网络的基本原理与局限。"
  },
